Comment_contributor: The Particle e marks the use of the Numeral as a Verb.
The difference between taŋahulu [<tanahulu>, with <n> in italics] and awala is not plain; the latter is always used for more than one ten.
The sum above ten and above a hundred is marked by ma, which is not a Conjunction.
[<tanahulu>, with <n> in italics; <na>, with <n> it italics]

Value: e rua awala ma na rua

Comment_contributor: [<tanarau>, with <n> in italics]; the word for hundred means the double frond, counted on both sides, as the word for ten means the double handful of fingers.
There is a word in use in Florida and Bugotu, mola, which is used indefinitely for a great number beyond count; and this, but doubtfully, is given in Malanta and Ulawa for a thousand.
